{{Infobox ancient site | name = Saru Maru | native_name = Saru Maru | alternate_name = | image = Saru Maru stupa.jpg | imagealttext = The great stupa of Saru Maru | caption = The great stupa of Saru Maru | map_type = India | relief = yes | map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|22.729949|N|77.519910|E|display=inline, title}} | location = | region = | type = Buddhist settlement, stupas and caves | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | height = | builder = | material = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = | cultures = | dependency_of = Pangoraria | occupants = | event = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | ownership = | public_access = | website = | notes = }}
'''Saru Maru''' is the archaeological site of an ancient monastic complex and [[Buddhist]] caves. The site is located near the village of Pangoraria, [[Budhani Tehsil]], [[Sehore District]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[India]].<ref name="Gupta">Gupta, The Origins of Indian Art, p.196</ref><ref name="ASI">[http://www.asibhopal.nic.in/monument/sehore_panguraria_sarcomprisedarea.html Archaeological Survey of India]</ref> The site is about 120&nbsp;km south of [[Sanchi]].
The site contains a number of stupas as well as natural caves for monks. In the caves many Buddhist graffiti have been found ([[swastika]], [[triratna]], [[kalasa]] ...). In the main cave were found two inscriptions of [[Ashoka]]: a version of the [[Minor Rock Edict]] n°1, one of the [[Edicts of Ashoka]], and another inscription mentioning the visit of Piyadasi (honorific name used by [[Ashoka]] in his inscriptions) as ''Maharahakumara'' (Prince).<ref name="Gupta" /><ref name="ASI" />
{{Quote|[[File:Panguraria Ashoka Commemorative inscription.jpg|thumb|100px|The commemorative inscription]] ''Piyadasi nama/ rajakumala va/ samvasamane/ imam desam papunitha/ viahara(ya)tay(e)
''The king, who (now after consecration) is called "Piyadasi", (once) came to this place for a pleasure tour while still a (ruling) prince, living together with his unwedded consort.'' | Commemorative Inscription of the visit of Ashoka, Saru Maru. Translated by Falk.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Allen |first1=Charles |title=Ashoka: The Search for India's Lost Emperor |date=2012 |publisher=Little, Brown Book Group |isbn=978-1-4087-0388-5 |pages=154-155 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K4vHjbUtf_4C&pg=PT154 |language=en}}</ref>}}
[[File:Saru Maru small stupas.jpg|thumb|left|Small stupas on the hill of Saru Maru.]] [[File:Saru-Maru Ashoka inscription.jpg|thumb|left|An inscription of Ashoka in one of the Saru Maru caves. It is a portion of [[Minor Rock Edict]] No.1.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sircar |first1=D. C. |title=Asokan studies |date=1979 || others=Plate XVI |url=https://archive.org/stream/in.gov.ignca.67068/67068#page/n177/mode/2up}}</ref>]] According to the inscription, it would seem that [[Ashoka]] visited this Buddhist monastic complex while he was still a prince, and viceroy of the region of [[Madhya Pradesh]], while his residence was to be at [[Vidisha]] <ref name="Gupta" />. In the Buddhist tradition, Ashoka's wife was called Vidishadevi, who was from [[Sanchi]], and whom he married in [[Vidisha]].
